class KthLargest {
    priority_queue<int, vector<int>, greater<int>> minHeap;
    int kth;
public:
    KthLargest(int k, vector<int>& nums) {
        kth = k;
        for (int n : nums) {
            minHeap.push(n);
            if (minHeap.size() > k) minHeap.pop();
        }
    }

    int add(int val) {
        minHeap.push(val);
        if (minHeap.size() > kth) minHeap.pop();
        return minHeap.top();
    }
};
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(log k) per add, O(n log k) for constructor
space complexity: O(k)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: Maintain a min-heap of size k; the root is always the kth largest. Constructor builds the heap in O(n log k). Each add inserts and pops once, giving O(log k). Space is bounded by k, so memory footprint is small and energy-efficient.

